The **human brain** is the central [organ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organ_\(biology\)) of the [nervous system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nervous_system), and with the [spinal cord](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal_cord), comprises the [central nervous system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_nervous_system). It consists of the [cerebrum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebrum), the [brainstem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brainstem) and the [cerebellum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellum). The brain controls most of the activities of the [body](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_body), processing, integrating, and coordinating the information it receives from the [sensory nervous system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensory_nervous_system). The brain integrates sensory information and coordinates instructions sent to the rest of the body.

The cerebrum, the largest part of the human brain, consists of two [cerebral hemispheres](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_hemisphere). Each hemisphere has an inner core composed of [white matter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_matter), and an outer surface – the [cerebral cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_cortex) – composed of [grey matter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_matter). The cortex has an outer layer, the [neocortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neocortex), and an inner [allocortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allocortex). The neocortex is made up of six [neuronal layers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_cortex#Layers_of_neocortex), while the allocortex has three or four. Each hemisphere is divided into four [lobes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lobes_of_the_brain) – the [frontal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frontal_lobe), [parietal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parietal_lobe), [temporal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporal_lobe), and [occipital lobes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occipital_lobe). The frontal lobe is associated with [executive functions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Executive_functions) including [self-control](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-control), [planning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planning), [reasoning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reason), and [abstract thought](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstraction), while the [occipital lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occipital_lobe) is dedicated to vision. Within each lobe, cortical areas are associated with specific functions, such as the [sensory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensory_cortex), [motor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_cortex), and [association](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_cortex#Association_areas) regions. Although the left and right hemispheres are broadly similar in shape and function, some functions are [associated with one side](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateralization_of_brain_function), such as [language](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language) in the left and [visual-spatial ability](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spatial_visualization_ability) in the right. The hemispheres are connected by [commissural nerve tracts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commissural_fiber), the largest being the [corpus callosum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corpus_callosum).

The cerebrum is connected by the brainstem to the spinal cord. The brainstem consists of the [midbrain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midbrain), the [pons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pons), and the [medulla oblongata](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medulla_oblongata). The [cerebellum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellum) is connected to the brainstem by three pairs of [nerve tracts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nerve_tract) called [cerebellar peduncles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellar_peduncle). Within the cerebrum is the [ventricular system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventricular_system), consisting of four interconnected [ventricles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventricular_system#Structure) in which [cerebrospinal fluid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebrospinal_fluid) is produced and circulated. Underneath the cerebral cortex are several structures, including the [thalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thalamus), the [epithalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epithalamus), the [pineal gland](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pineal_gland), the [hypothalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypothalamus), the [pituitary gland](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pituitary_gland), and the [subthalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subthalamus); the [limbic structures](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limbic_system), including the [amygdalae](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amygdala) and the [hippocampi](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippocampus), the [claustrum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claustrum), the various [nuclei](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nucleus_\(neuroanatomy\)) of the [basal ganglia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basal_ganglia), the [basal forebrain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basal_forebrain) structures, and three [circumventricular organs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circumventricular_organ). Brain structures that are not on the midplane exist in pairs; for example, there are two hippocampi and two amygdalae.

The [cells of the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_cell) include [neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuron) and supportive [glial cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroglia). There are more than 86 billion neurons in the brain, and a more or less equal number of other cells. Brain activity is made possible by the interconnections of neurons and their release of [neurotransmitters](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotransmitter) in response to [nerve impulses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_potential). Neurons connect to form [neural pathways](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_pathway), [neural circuits](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_circuit), and elaborate [network systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large-scale_brain_networks). The whole circuitry is driven by the process of [neurotransmission](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotransmission).

The brain is protected by the [skull](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skull#Humans), suspended in [cerebrospinal fluid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebrospinal_fluid), and isolated from the [bloodstream](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circulatory_system) by the [blood–brain barrier](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood%E2%80%93brain_barrier). However, the brain is still susceptible to [damage](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_damage), [disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_nervous_system_disease), and [infection](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infection). Damage can be caused by [trauma](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closed_head_injury), or a loss of blood supply known as a [stroke](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroke). The brain is susceptible to [degenerative disorders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurodegeneration), such as [Parkinson's disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parkinson%27s_disease), [dementias](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dementia) including [Alzheimer's disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alzheimer%27s_disease), and [multiple sclerosis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_sclerosis). [Psychiatric conditions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychiatric_condition), including [schizophrenia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schizophrenia) and [clinical depression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_depressive_disorder), are thought to be associated with brain dysfunctions. The brain can also be the site of [tumours](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_tumors), both [benign](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benign_tumour) and [malignant](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cancer); these mostly [originate from other sites in the body](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metastasis).

The study of the anatomy of the brain is [neuroanatomy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroanatomy), while the study of its function is [neuroscience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroscience). Numerous techniques are used to study the brain. [Specimens](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biological_specimen) from other animals, which may be [examined microscopically](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Histology), have traditionally provided much information. [Medical imaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_imaging) technologies such as [functional neuroimaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_neuroimaging), and [electroencephalography](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electroencephalography) (EEG) recordings are important in studying the brain. The [medical history](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_history) of people with [brain injury](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_damage) has provided insight into the function of each part of the brain. Neuroscience research has expanded considerably, and research is ongoing.

In culture, the [philosophy of mind](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy_of_mind) has for centuries attempted to address the question of the nature of [consciousness](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consciousness) and the [mind–body problem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mind%E2%80%93body_problem). The [pseudoscience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudoscience) of [phrenology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phrenology) attempted to localise personality attributes to regions of the cortex in the 19th century. [In science fiction, brain transplants](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_transplant#In_science_fiction) are imagined in tales such as the 1942 [*Donovan's Brain*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donovan%27s_Brain).

**Gross anatomy**

*See also: [Evolution of the brain § Evolution of the human brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_of_the_brain#Evolution_of_the_human_brain), and [Neuroscience of sex differences](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroscience_of_sex_differences)*

The adult human brain weighs on average about 1.2–1.4 kg (2.6–3.1 lb) which is about 2% of the total body weight,[\[2\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-CarpenterCh1-2)[\[3\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Bigos-3) with a volume of around 1260 [cm3](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_centimetre) in men and 1130 cm3 in women.[\[4\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Cosgrove-4) There is substantial individual variation,[\[4\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Cosgrove-4) with the standard [reference range](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_range) for men being 1,180–1,620 g (2.60–3.57 lb)[\[5\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-MolinaDiMaio2012-5) and for women 1,030–1,400 g (2.27–3.09 lb).[\[6\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-MolinaDiMaio2015-6)

The [cerebrum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebrum), consisting of the [cerebral hemispheres](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_hemisphere), forms the largest part of the brain and overlies the other brain structures.[\[7\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008227%E2%80%939-7) The outer region of the hemispheres, the [cerebral cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_cortex), is [grey matter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_matter), consisting of [cortical layers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_cortex#Layers) of [neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuron). Each hemisphere is divided into four main [lobes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lobes_of_the_brain) – the [frontal lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frontal_lobe), [parietal lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parietal_lobe), [temporal lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporal_lobe), and [occipital lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occipital_lobe).[\[8\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008335%E2%80%937-8) Three other lobes are included by some sources which are a *central lobe*, a [limbic lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limbic_lobe), and an [insular lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insular_cortex).[\[9\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Ribas-9) The central lobe comprises the [precentral gyrus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Precentral_gyrus) and the [postcentral gyrus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Postcentral_gyrus) and is included since it forms a distinct functional role.[\[9\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Ribas-9)[\[10\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Frigeri-10)

The [brainstem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brainstem), resembling a stalk, attaches to and leaves the cerebrum at the start of the [midbrain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midbrain) area. The brainstem includes the midbrain, the [pons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pons), and the [medulla oblongata](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medulla_oblongata). Behind the brainstem is the [cerebellum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellum) ([Latin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_language): *little brain*).[\[7\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008227%E2%80%939-7)

The cerebrum, brainstem, cerebellum, and spinal cord are covered by three membranes called [meninges](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meninges). The membranes are the tough [dura mater](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dura_mater); the middle [arachnoid mater](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arachnoid_mater) and the more delicate inner [pia mater](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pia_mater). Between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater is the [subarachnoid space](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meninges#Subarachnoid_space) and [subarachnoid cisterns](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarachnoid_cisterns), which contain the [cerebrospinal fluid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebrospinal_fluid).[\[11\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPurves2012724-11) The outermost membrane of the cerebral cortex is the basement membrane of the pia mater called the [glia limitans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glia_limitans) and is an important part of the [blood–brain barrier](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood%E2%80%93brain_barrier).[\[12\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Anatomy_and_Ultrastructure-12) In 2023 a fourth meningeal membrane has been proposed known as the [subarachnoid lymphatic-like membrane](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarachnoid_lymphatic-like_membrane).[\[13\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Fluids_barriers-13)[\[14\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Neuhuber-14) The living brain is very soft, having a gel-like consistency similar to soft tofu.[\[15\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NPR-15) The cortical layers of neurons constitute much of the cerebral [grey matter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_matter), while the deeper subcortical regions of [myelinated](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myelin) [axons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axon), make up the [white matter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_matter).[\[7\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008227%E2%80%939-7) The white matter of the brain makes up about half of the total brain volume.[\[16\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Neuron-16)

**Cerebrum**

*Main articles: [Cerebrum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebrum) and [Cerebral cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_cortex)*

*![][image3]*

Major gyri and sulci on the lateral surface of the cortex

Lobes of the brain

The cerebrum is the largest part of the brain and is divided into nearly [symmetrical](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry_in_biology#Bilateral_symmetry) left and right [hemispheres](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_hemisphere) by a deep groove, the [longitudinal fissure](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longitudinal_fissure).[\[17\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Davey-17) Asymmetry between the lobes is noted as a [petalia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paleoneurobiology#Asymmetry).[\[18\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-18) The hemispheres are connected by five [commissures](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commissural_fiber#Structure) that span the longitudinal fissure, the largest of these is the [corpus callosum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corpus_callosum).[\[7\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008227%E2%80%939-7) Each hemisphere is conventionally divided into four main [lobes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lobes_of_the_brain); the [frontal lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frontal_lobe), [parietal lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parietal_lobe), [temporal lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporal_lobe), and [occipital lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occipital_lobe), named according to the [skull bones](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skull) that overlie them.[\[8\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008335%E2%80%937-8) Each lobe is associated with one or two specialised functions though there is some functional overlap between them.[\[19\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Ackerman-19) The surface of the brain is [folded](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gyrification) into ridges ([gyri](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gyrus)) and grooves ([sulci](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sulcus_\(neuroanatomy\))), many of which are named, usually according to their position, such as the [frontal gyrus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frontal_gyrus) of the frontal lobe or the [central sulcus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_sulcus) separating the central regions of the hemispheres. There are many small variations in the secondary and tertiary folds.[\[20\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen2001455%E2%80%93456-20)

The outer part of the cerebrum is the [cerebral cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_cortex), made up of [grey matter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_matter) arranged in layers. It is 2 to 4 millimetres (0.079 to 0.157 in) thick, and deeply folded to give a convoluted appearance.[\[21\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-21) Beneath the cortex is the cerebral [white matter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_matter). The largest part of the cerebral cortex is the [neocortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neocortex), which has six neuronal layers. The rest of the cortex is of [allocortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allocortex), which has three or four layers.[\[7\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008227%E2%80%939-7)

The cortex is [mapped](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_mapping) by divisions into about fifty different functional areas known as [Brodmann's areas](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brodmann%27s_areas). These areas are distinctly different when [seen under a microscope](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Histology).[\[22\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011574-22) The cortex is divided into two main functional areas – a [motor cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_cortex) and a [sensory cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensory_cortex).[\[23\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011667-23) The [primary motor cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primary_motor_cortex), which sends axons down to [motor neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_neuron) in the brainstem and spinal cord, occupies the rear portion of the frontal lobe, directly in front of the somatosensory area. The [primary sensory areas](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primary_sensory_areas) receive signals from the [sensory nerves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensory_nerve) and [tracts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nerve_tract) by way of [relay nuclei](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thalamus#Thalamic_nuclei) in the [thalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thalamus). Primary sensory areas include the [visual cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_cortex) of the [occipital lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occipital_lobe), the [auditory cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auditory_cortex) in parts of the [temporal lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporal_lobe) and [insular cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insular_cortex), and the [somatosensory cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Somatosensory_cortex) in the [parietal lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parietal_lobe). The remaining parts of the cortex are called the [association areas](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_areas). These areas receive input from the sensory areas and lower parts of the brain and are involved in the complex [cognitive processes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognition) of [perception](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perception), [thought](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thought), and [decision-making](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision-making).[\[24\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-24) The main functions of the frontal lobe are to [control attention](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attentional_control), abstract thinking, behaviour, problem-solving tasks, and physical reactions and personality.[\[25\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Freberg-25)[\[26\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kolb-26) The occipital lobe is the smallest lobe; its main functions are visual reception, visual-spatial processing, movement, and [colour recognition](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_vision#Color_in_the_primate_brain).[\[25\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Freberg-25)[\[26\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kolb-26) There is a smaller occipital lobule in the lobe known as the [cuneus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuneus). The temporal lobe controls [auditory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Echoic_memory) and [visual memories](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_memory), [language](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_processing_in_the_brain), and some hearing and speech.[\[25\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Freberg-25)

![][image4]

Cortical folds and white matter in horizontal bisection of head

The cerebrum contains the [ventricles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventricular_system) where the cerebrospinal fluid is produced and circulated. Below the corpus callosum is the [septum pellucidum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Septum_pellucidum), a membrane that separates the [lateral ventricles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_ventricles). Beneath the lateral ventricles is the [thalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thalamus) and to the front and below is the [hypothalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypothalamus). The hypothalamus leads on to the [pituitary gland](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pituitary_gland). At the back of the thalamus is the brainstem.[\[27\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPocock200664-27)

The [basal ganglia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basal_ganglia), also called basal nuclei, are a set of structures deep within the hemispheres involved in behaviour and movement regulation.[\[28\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPurves2012399-28) The largest component is the [striatum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Striatum), others are the [globus pallidus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Globus_pallidus), the [substantia nigra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Substantia_nigra) and the [subthalamic nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subthalamic_nucleus).[\[28\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPurves2012399-28) The striatum is divided into a ventral striatum, and dorsal striatum, subdivisions that are based upon function and connections. The ventral striatum consists of the [nucleus accumbens](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nucleus_accumbens) and the [olfactory tubercle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olfactory_tubercle) whereas the dorsal striatum consists of the [caudate nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caudate_nucleus) and the [putamen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Putamen). The putamen and the globus pallidus lie separated from the lateral ventricles and thalamus by the [internal capsule](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_capsule), whereas the caudate nucleus stretches around and abuts the lateral ventricles on their outer sides.[\[29\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008325%E2%80%936-29) At the deepest part of the [lateral sulcus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_sulcus) between the [insular cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insular_cortex) and the striatum is a thin neuronal sheet called the [claustrum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claustrum).[\[30\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Goll-30)

Below and in front of the striatum are a number of [basal forebrain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basal_forebrain) structures. These include the [nucleus basalis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nucleus_basalis), [diagonal band of Broca](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diagonal_band_of_Broca), [substantia innominata](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Substantia_innominata), and the [medial septal nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medial_septal_nucleus). These structures are important in producing the [neurotransmitter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotransmitter), [acetylcholine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acetylcholine), which is then distributed widely throughout the brain. The basal forebrain, in particular the nucleus basalis, is considered to be the major [cholinergic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cholinergic) output of the central nervous system to the striatum and neocortex.[\[31\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Goard-31)

**Cerebellum**

Human brain viewed from below, showing cerebellum and brainstem

*Main article: [Cerebellum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellum)*

The cerebellum is divided into an [anterior lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_lobe_of_cerebellum), a [posterior lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_lobe_of_cerebellum), and the [flocculonodular lobe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flocculonodular_lobe).[\[32\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011699-32) The anterior and posterior lobes are connected in the middle by the [vermis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellar_vermis).[\[33\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008298-33) Compared to the cerebral cortex, the cerebellum has a much thinner outer cortex that is narrowly furrowed into numerous curved transverse fissures.[\[33\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008298-33) Viewed from underneath between the two lobes is the third lobe the flocculonodular lobe.[\[34\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-34) The cerebellum rests at the back of the [cranial cavity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_cranial_fossa), lying beneath the occipital lobes, and is separated from these by the [cerebellar tentorium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellar_tentorium), a sheet of fibre.[\[35\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008297-35)

It is connected to the brainstem by three pairs of [nerve tracts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nerve_tract) called [cerebellar peduncles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellar_peduncle). The [superior pair](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superior_cerebellar_peduncle) connects to the midbrain; the [middle pair](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_cerebellar_peduncle) connects to the medulla, and the [inferior pair](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inferior_cerebellar_peduncle) connects to the pons.[\[33\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008298-33) The cerebellum consists of an inner medulla of white matter and an outer cortex of richly folded grey matter.[\[35\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008297-35) The cerebellum's anterior and posterior lobes appear to play a role in the coordination and smoothing of complex motor movements, and the flocculonodular lobe in the maintenance of [balance](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equilibrioception)[\[36\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011698%E2%80%939-36) although debate exists as to its cognitive, behavioural and motor functions.[\[37\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTESquire2013761%E2%80%93763-37)

**Brainstem**

*Main article: [Brainstem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brainstem)*

The brainstem lies beneath the cerebrum and consists of the [midbrain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midbrain), [pons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pons) and [medulla](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medulla_oblongata). It lies in the [back part of the skull](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_cranial_fossa), resting on the part of the [base](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_of_the_skull) known as the [clivus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clivus_\(anatomy\)), and ends at the [foramen magnum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foramen_magnum), a large [opening](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/foramen) in the [occipital bone](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occipital_bone). The brainstem continues below this as the [spinal cord](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal_cord),[\[38\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008275-38) protected by the [vertebral column](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertebral_column).

Ten of the twelve pairs of [cranial nerves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cranial_nerve)[\[a\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-39) emerge directly from the brainstem.[\[38\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008275-38) The brainstem also contains many [cranial nerve nuclei](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cranial_nerve_nucleus) and [nuclei](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nucleus_\(neuroanatomy\)) of [peripheral nerves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nerve), as well as nuclei involved in the regulation of many essential processes including [breathing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breathing), control of eye movements and balance.[\[39\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011691-40)[\[38\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008275-38) The [reticular formation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reticular_formation), a network of nuclei of ill-defined formation, is present within and along the length of the brainstem.[\[38\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008275-38) Many [nerve tracts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nerve_tract), which transmit information to and from the cerebral cortex to the rest of the body, pass through the brainstem.[\[38\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008275-38)

**Microanatomy**

The human brain is primarily composed of [neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuron), [glial cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glial_cell), [neural stem cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_stem_cell), and [blood vessels](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_vessel). Types of neuron include [interneurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interneuron), [pyramidal cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramidal_cell) including [Betz cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betz_cell), [motor neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_neuron) ([upper](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Upper_motor_neuron) and [lower motor neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lower_motor_neuron)), and cerebellar [Purkinje cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purkinje_cell). Betz cells are the largest cells (by size of cell body) in the nervous system.[\[40\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPurves2012377-41) The adult human brain is estimated to contain 86±8 billion neurons, with a roughly equal number (85±10 billion) of non-neuronal cells.[\[41\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-:1-42) Out of these neurons, 16 billion (19%) are located in the cerebral cortex, and 69 billion (80%) are in the cerebellum.[\[3\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Bigos-3)[\[41\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-:1-42)

Types of glial cell are [astrocytes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astrocyte) (including [Bergmann glia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bergmann_glia)), [oligodendrocytes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligodendrocyte), [ependymal cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ependymal_cell) (including [tanycytes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tanycyte)), [radial glial cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radial_glial_cell), [microglia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microglia), and a subtype of [oligodendrocyte progenitor cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligodendrocyte_progenitor_cell). Astrocytes are the largest of the glial cells. They are [stellate cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stellate_cell) with many processes radiating from their [cell bodies](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soma_\(biology\)). Some of these processes end as perivascular [endfeet](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endfeet) on [capillary](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capillary) walls.[\[42\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-43) The [glia limitans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glia_limitans) of the cortex is made up of [astrocyte endfeet processes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astrocyte_endfeet) that serve in part to contain the cells of the brain.[\[12\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Anatomy_and_Ultrastructure-12)

[Mast cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mast_cell) are [white blood cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_blood_cell) that interact in the [neuroimmune system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroimmune_system) in the brain.[\[43\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Mast_cell_neuroimmmune_system-44) Mast cells in the central nervous system are present in [a number of structures](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mast_cell#In_the_nervous_system) including the meninges;[\[43\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Mast_cell_neuroimmmune_system-44) they mediate neuroimmune responses in inflammatory conditions and help to maintain the blood–brain barrier, particularly in brain regions where the barrier is absent.[\[43\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Mast_cell_neuroimmmune_system-44)[\[44\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011748%E2%80%93749-45) Mast cells serve the same general functions in the body and central nervous system, such as effecting or regulating allergic responses, [innate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Innate_immune_system) and [adaptive immunity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adaptive_immune_system), [autoimmunity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autoimmunity), and [inflammation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inflammation).[\[43\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Mast_cell_neuroimmmune_system-44) Mast cells serve as the main [effector cell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effector_cell) through which pathogens can affect the [biochemical signaling that takes place between the gastrointestinal tract and the central nervous system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gut-brain_axis).[\[45\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-pmid24833851-46)[\[46\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Microbiome-CNS-ENS-47)

Some 400 [genes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene) are shown to be brain-specific. In all neurons, [ELAVL3](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ELAVL3) is expressed, and in pyramidal cells, [NRGN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NRGN) and [REEP2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/REEP2) are also expressed. [GAD1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GAD1) – essential for the biosynthesis of the neurotransmitter [GABA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GABA) – is expressed in interneurons. Proteins expressed in glial cells include astrocyte markers [GFAP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glial_fibrillary_acidic_protein) and [S100B](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S100B) whereas [myelin basic protein](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myelin_basic_protein) and the transcription factor [OLIG2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OLIG2) are expressed in oligodendrocytes.[\[47\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-48)

**Cerebrospinal fluid**

**![][image5]**

[Cerebrospinal fluid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebrospinal_fluid) circulates in spaces around and within the brain

*Main article: [Cerebrospinal fluid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebrospinal_fluid)*

Cerebrospinal fluid is a clear, colourless [transcellular fluid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcellular_fluid) that circulates around the brain in the [subarachnoid space](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarachnoid_space), in the [ventricular system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventricular_system), and in the [central canal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_canal) of the spinal cord. It also fills some gaps in the subarachnoid space, known as [subarachnoid cisterns](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarachnoid_cisterns).[\[48\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008242%E2%80%93244-49) The four ventricles, two [lateral](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_ventricle), a [third](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_ventricle), and a [fourth ventricle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourth_ventricle), all contain a [choroid plexus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choroid_plexus) that produces cerebrospinal fluid.[\[49\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPurves2012742-50) The third ventricle lies in the midline and [is connected](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interventricular_foramina_\(neuroanatomy\)) to the lateral ventricles.[\[48\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008242%E2%80%93244-49) A single [duct](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duct_\(anatomy\)), the [cerebral aqueduct](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_aqueduct) between the pons and the cerebellum, connects the third ventricle to the fourth ventricle.[\[50\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008243-51) Three separate openings, the [middle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medial_aperture) and two [lateral apertures](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_aperture), drain the cerebrospinal fluid from the fourth ventricle to the [cisterna magna](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cisterna_magna), one of the major cisterns. From here, cerebrospinal fluid circulates around the brain and spinal cord in the subarachnoid space, between the arachnoid mater and pia mater.[\[48\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008242%E2%80%93244-49) At any one time, there is about 150mL of cerebrospinal fluid – most within the subarachnoid space. It is constantly being regenerated and absorbed, and is replaced about once every 5–6 hours.[\[48\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008242%E2%80%93244-49)

A [glymphatic system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glymphatic_system) has been described as the lymphatic drainage system of the brain.[\[51\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Yankova2021-52)[\[52\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Glymphatic_system_and_brain_waste_clearance_2017_review-53) The brain-wide glymphatic pathway includes drainage routes from the cerebrospinal fluid, and from the [meningeal lymphatic vessels](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meningeal_lymphatic_vessels) that are associated with the [dural sinuses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dural_sinuses), and run alongside the cerebral blood vessels.[\[53\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-D-O-54)[\[54\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Sun-55) The pathway drains [interstitial fluid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interstitial_fluid) from the tissue of the brain.[\[54\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Sun-55)

**Blood supply**

*Main article: [Cerebral circulation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_circulation)*

*![][image6]*

Two circulations joining at the circle of Willis (inferior view)

![][image7]

Diagram showing features of cerebral [outer membranes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meninges) and supply of blood vessels

The [internal carotid arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_carotid_arteries) supply [oxygenated blood](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood#Oxygen_transport) to the front of the brain and the [vertebral arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertebral_arteries) supply blood to the back of the brain.[\[55\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008247-56) These two circulations [join](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anastomosis) in the [circle of Willis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle_of_Willis), a ring of connected arteries that lies in the [interpeduncular cistern](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interpeduncular_cistern) between the midbrain and pons.[\[56\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008251%E2%80%932-57)

The internal carotid arteries are branches of the [common carotid arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_carotid_arteries). They enter the [cranium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cranium) through the [carotid canal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carotid_canal), travel through the [cavernous sinus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cavernous_sinus) and enter the [subarachnoid space](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarachnoid_space).[\[57\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008250-58) They then enter the [circle of Willis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle_of_Willis), with two branches, the [anterior cerebral arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_cerebral_arteries) emerging. These branches travel forward and then upward along the [longitudinal fissure](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longitudinal_fissure), and supply the front and midline parts of the brain.[\[58\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008248-59) One or more small [anterior communicating arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_communicating_artery) join the two anterior cerebral arteries shortly after they emerge as branches.[\[58\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008248-59) The internal carotid arteries continue forward as the [middle cerebral arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_cerebral_arteries). They travel sideways along the [sphenoid bone](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphenoid_bone) of the [eye socket](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orbit_\(anatomy\)), then upwards through the [insula cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insula_cortex), where final branches arise. The middle cerebral arteries send branches along their length.[\[57\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008250-58)

The vertebral arteries emerge as branches of the left and right [subclavian arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subclavian_arteries). They travel upward through [transverse foramina](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertebra#Cervical_vertebrae) which are spaces in the [cervical vertebrae](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cervical_vertebrae). Each side enters the cranial cavity through the foramen magnum along the corresponding side of the medulla.[\[57\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008250-58) They give off [one of the three cerebellar branches](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_inferior_cerebellar_artery). The vertebral arteries join in front of the middle part of the medulla to form the larger [basilar artery](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basilar_artery), which sends multiple branches to supply the medulla and pons, and the two other [anterior](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_inferior_cerebellar_artery) and [superior cerebellar branches](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superior_cerebellar_artery).[\[59\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008251-60) Finally, the basilar artery divides into two [posterior cerebral arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_cerebral_arteries). These travel outwards, around the superior cerebellar peduncles, and along the top of the cerebellar tentorium, where it sends branches to supply the temporal and occipital lobes.[\[59\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008251-60) Each posterior cerebral artery sends a small [posterior communicating artery](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_communicating_artery) to join with the internal carotid arteries.

**Blood drainage**

[Cerebral veins](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_veins) drain [deoxygenated blood](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood#Oxygen_transport) from the brain. The brain has two main networks of [veins](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vein): an exterior or [superficial network](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superior_cerebral_veins), on the surface of the cerebrum that has three branches, and an [interior network](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_cerebral_veins). These two networks communicate via [anastomosing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anastomosis) (joining) veins.[\[60\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008254%E2%80%936-61) The veins of the brain drain into larger cavities of the [dural venous sinuses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dural_venous_sinuses) usually situated between the dura mater and the covering of the skull.[\[61\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEElsevier's2007311%E2%80%934-62) Blood from the cerebellum and midbrain drains into the [great cerebral vein](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_cerebral_vein). Blood from the medulla and pons of the brainstem have a variable pattern of drainage, either into the [spinal veins](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal_veins) or into adjacent cerebral veins.[\[60\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008254%E2%80%936-61)

The blood in the [deep](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anatomical_terms_of_location#deep) part of the brain drains, through a [venous plexus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venous_plexus) into the [cavernous sinus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cavernous_sinus) at the front, and the [superior](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superior_petrosal_sinus) and [inferior petrosal sinuses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inferior_petrosal_sinus) at the sides, and the [inferior sagittal sinus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inferior_sagittal_sinus) at the back.[\[61\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEElsevier's2007311%E2%80%934-62) Blood drains from the outer brain into the large [superior sagittal sinus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superior_sagittal_sinus), which rests in the midline on top of the brain. Blood from here joins with blood from the [straight sinus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Straight_sinus) at the [confluence of sinuses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confluence_of_sinuses).[\[61\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEElsevier's2007311%E2%80%934-62)

Blood from here drains into the left and right [transverse sinuses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transverse_sinus).[\[61\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEElsevier's2007311%E2%80%934-62) These then drain into the [sigmoid sinuses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigmoid_sinus), which receive blood from the cavernous sinus and superior and inferior petrosal sinuses. The sigmoid drains into the large [internal jugular veins](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_jugular_vein).[\[61\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEElsevier's2007311%E2%80%934-62)[\[60\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray's_Anatomy2008254%E2%80%936-61)

**The blood–brain barrier**

The larger arteries throughout the brain supply blood to smaller [capillaries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capillaries). These smallest of [blood vessels](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_vessel) in the brain, are lined with cells joined by [tight junctions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tight_junction) and so fluids do not seep in or leak out to the same degree as they do in other capillaries; this creates the [blood–brain barrier](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood%E2%80%93brain_barrier).[\[44\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011748%E2%80%93749-45) [Pericytes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pericyte) play a major role in the formation of the tight junctions.[\[62\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Daneman-63) The barrier is less permeable to larger molecules, but is still permeable to water, carbon dioxide, oxygen, and most fat-soluble substances (including [anaesthetics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anaesthetic) and alcohol).[\[44\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011748%E2%80%93749-45) The blood-brain barrier is not present in the [circumventricular organs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circumventricular_organs)—which are structures in the brain that may need to respond to changes in body fluids—such as the [pineal gland](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pineal_gland), [area postrema](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_postrema), and some areas of the [hypothalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypothalamus).[\[44\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011748%E2%80%93749-45) There is a similar [blood–cerebrospinal fluid barrier](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choroid_plexus#Function), which serves the same purpose as the blood–brain barrier, but facilitates the transport of different substances into the brain due to the distinct structural characteristics between the two barrier systems.[\[44\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011748%E2%80%93749-45)[\[63\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-BCSF-64)

**Development**

*Main article: [Development of the nervous system in humans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Development_of_the_nervous_system_in_humans)*

*Further information: [Development of the human brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Development_of_the_human_brain)*

Neurulation and neural crest cells

Simple drawing of the lateral view of the three primary vesicle stage of the three to four week old embryo shown in different colors, and the five secondary vesicle stage of the five week old embryo shown in different colors and a lateral view of this

Primary and secondary [vesicle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_vesicle) stages of development in the early embryo to the fifth week

![Very simple drawing of the front end of a human embryo, showing each vesicle of the developing brain in a different color.][image8]

Brain of a human embryo in the sixth week of development

At the beginning of the third week of [development](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_embryonic_development), the [embryonic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embryo) [ectoderm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ectoderm) forms a thickened strip called the [neural plate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_plate).[\[64\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Sadler-65) By the fourth week of development the neural plate has widened to give a broad [cephalic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cephalization) end, a less broad middle part and a narrow caudal end. These swellings are known as the [primary brain vesicles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_vesicle) and represent the beginnings of the [forebrain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forebrain) (prosencephalon), [midbrain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midbrain) (mesencephalon), and [hindbrain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindbrain) (rhombencephalon).[\[65\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen2001419-66)[\[66\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-67)

[Neural crest cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_crest) (derived from the ectoderm) populate the lateral edges of the plate at the [neural folds](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_fold). In the fourth week—during the [neurulation stage](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurulation)—the [neural folds close](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_fold#Folding_mechanism) to form the [neural tube](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_tube), bringing together the neural crest cells at the [neural crest](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_crest).[\[67\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen200185%E2%80%9388-68) The neural crest runs the length of the tube with cranial neural crest cells at the cephalic end and caudal neural crest cells at the tail. Cells detach from the crest and [migrate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_migration) in a craniocaudal (head to tail) wave inside the tube.[\[67\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen200185%E2%80%9388-68) Cells at the cephalic end give rise to the brain, and cells at the caudal end give rise to the spinal cord.[\[68\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPurves2012480%E2%80%93482-69)

The tube [flexes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flexure_\(embryology\)) as it grows, forming the crescent-shaped cerebral hemispheres at the head. The cerebral hemispheres first appear on day 32\.[\[69\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen2001445%E2%80%93446-70) Early in the fourth week, the cephalic part bends sharply forward in a [cephalic flexure](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cephalic_flexure).[\[67\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen200185%E2%80%9388-68) This flexed part becomes the forebrain (prosencephalon); the adjoining curving part becomes the midbrain (mesencephalon) and the part caudal to the flexure becomes the hindbrain (rhombencephalon). These areas are formed as swellings known as the three [primary brain vesicles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_vesicle). In the fifth week of development five [secondary brain vesicles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_vesicle) have formed.[\[70\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-71) The forebrain separates into two vesicles – an anterior [telencephalon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telencephalon) and a posterior [diencephalon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diencephalon). The telencephalon gives rise to the cerebral cortex, basal ganglia, and related structures. The diencephalon gives rise to the thalamus and hypothalamus. The hindbrain also splits into two areas – the [metencephalon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metencephalon) and the [myelencephalon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myelencephalon). The metencephalon gives rise to the cerebellum and pons. The myelencephalon gives rise to the medulla oblongata.[\[71\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen200185%E2%80%9387-72) Also during the fifth week, the brain divides into [repeating segments](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Segmentation_\(biology\)) called [neuromeres](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuromere).[\[65\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen2001419-66)[\[72\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPurves2012481%E2%80%93484-73) In the [hindbrain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindbrain) these are known as [rhombomeres](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombomere).[\[73\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Neuro-74)

A characteristic of the brain is the cortical folding known as [gyrification](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gyrification). For just over five months of [prenatal development](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prenatal_development) the cortex is smooth. By the gestational age of 24 weeks, the wrinkled morphology showing the fissures that begin to mark out the lobes of the brain is evident.[\[74\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Chen-75) Why the cortex wrinkles and folds is not well-understood, but gyrification has been linked to intelligence and [neurological disorders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurological_disorder), and a [number of gyrification theories](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gyrification#Theories_on_causality_in_gyrification) have been proposed.[\[74\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Chen-75) These theories include those based on [mechanical buckling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gyrification#Mechanical_buckling),[\[75\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Ronan-76)[\[19\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Ackerman-19) [axonal tension](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gyrification#Axonal_tension),[\[76\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Van_Essen-77) and [differential tangential expansion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gyrification#Differential_tangential_expansion).[\[75\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Ronan-76) What is clear is that gyrification is not a random process, but rather a complex developmentally predetermined process which generates patterns of folds that are consistent between individuals and most species.[\[75\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Ronan-76)[\[77\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Borrell-78)

The first groove to appear in the fourth month is the lateral cerebral fossa.[\[69\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen2001445%E2%80%93446-70) The expanding caudal end of the hemisphere has to curve over in a forward direction to fit into the restricted space. This covers the fossa and turns it into a much deeper ridge known as the [lateral sulcus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_sulcus) and this marks out the temporal lobe.[\[69\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen2001445%E2%80%93446-70) By the sixth month other sulci have formed that demarcate the frontal, parietal, and occipital lobes.[\[69\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTELarsen2001445%E2%80%93446-70) A gene present in the human genome ([ARHGAP11B](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARHGAP11B)) may play a major role in gyrification and encephalisation.[\[78\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-79)
