**Function**

Motor and sensory regions of the brain

**Motor control**

The frontal lobe is involved in reasoning, motor control, emotion, and language. It contains the [motor cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_cortex), which is involved in planning and coordinating movement; the [prefrontal cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prefrontal_cortex), which is responsible for higher-level cognitive functioning; and [Broca's area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broca%27s_area), which is essential for language production.[\[79\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-80) The [motor system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_system) of the brain is responsible for the [generation and control](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_control) of movement.[\[80\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011685-81) Generated movements pass from the brain through nerves to [motor neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_neuron) in the body, which control the action of [muscles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muscle). The [corticospinal tract](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corticospinal_tract) carries movements from the brain, through the [spinal cord](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal_cord), to the torso and limbs.[\[81\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011687-82) The [cranial nerves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cranial_nerves) carry movements related to the eyes, mouth and face.

Gross movement – such as [locomotion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animal_locomotion) and the movement of arms and legs – is generated in the [motor cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_cortex), divided into three parts: the [primary motor cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primary_motor_cortex), found in the [precentral gyrus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Precentral_gyrus) and has sections dedicated to the movement of different body parts. These movements are supported and regulated by two other areas, lying [anterior](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior) to the primary motor cortex: the [premotor area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premotor_area) and the [supplementary motor area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supplementary_motor_area).[\[82\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011686-83) The hands and mouth have a much larger area dedicated to them than other body parts, allowing finer movement; this has been visualised in a [motor homunculus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cortical_homunculus#Types).[\[82\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011686-83) Impulses generated from the motor cortex travel along the [corticospinal tract](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corticospinal_tract) along the front of the medulla and cross over ([decussate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decussate)) at the [medullary pyramids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medullary_pyramids_\(brainstem\)). These then travel down the [spinal cord](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal_cord), with most connecting to [interneurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal_interneuron), in turn connecting to [lower motor neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lower_motor_neuron) within the [grey matter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_matter) that then transmit the impulse to move to muscles themselves.[\[81\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011687-82) The cerebellum and [basal ganglia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basal_ganglia), play a role in fine, complex and coordinated muscle movements.[\[83\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011698,_708-84) Connections between the cortex and the basal ganglia control muscle tone, posture and movement initiation, and are referred to as the [extrapyramidal system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extrapyramidal_system).[\[84\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101139-85)

**Sensory**

**![][image12]**

Cortical areas

Routing of neural signals from the two eyes to the brain

The [sensory nervous system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensory_nervous_system) is involved with the reception and processing of [sensory information](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sense). This information is received through the cranial nerves, through tracts in the spinal cord, and directly at centres of the brain exposed to the blood.[\[85\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Hellier-86) The brain also receives and interprets information from the [special senses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_sense) of [vision](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_perception), [smell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olfaction), [hearing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hearing), and [taste](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taste). [Mixed motor and sensory signals](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensory-motor_coupling) are also integrated.[\[85\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Hellier-86)

From the skin, the brain receives information about [fine touch](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Touch), [pressure](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure), [pain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pain), [vibration](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vibration) and [temperature](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperature). From the joints, the brain receives information about [joint position](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proprioception).[\[86\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011571%E2%80%93576-87) The [sensory cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensory_cortex) is found just near the motor cortex, and, like the motor cortex, has areas related to sensation from different body parts. Sensation collected by a [sensory receptor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensory_receptor) on the skin is changed to a nerve signal, that is passed up a series of neurons through tracts in the spinal cord. The [dorsal column–medial lemniscus pathway](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorsal_column%E2%80%93medial_lemniscus_pathway) contains information about fine touch, vibration and position of joints. The pathway fibres travel up the back part of the spinal cord to the back part of the medulla, where they connect with [second-order neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorsal_column%E2%80%93medial_lemniscus_pathway#Second-order_neurons) that immediately [send fibres across the midline](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decussation). These fibres then travel upwards into the [ventrobasal complex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventrobasal_complex) in the thalamus where they connect with [third-order neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorsal_column%E2%80%93medial_lemniscus_pathway#Third-order_neurons) which send fibres up to the sensory cortex.[\[86\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011571%E2%80%93576-87) The [spinothalamic tract](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinothalamic_tract) carries information about pain, temperature, and gross touch. The pathway fibres travel up the spinal cord and connect with second-order neurons in the [reticular formation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reticular_formation) of the brainstem for pain and temperature, and also terminate at the ventrobasal complex of the thalamus for gross touch.[\[87\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011573%E2%80%93574-88)

[Vision](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_perception) is generated by light that hits the [retina](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retina) of the eye. [Photoreceptors](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Photoreceptor_cell) in the retina [transduce](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_phototransduction) the sensory stimulus of [light](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light) into an electrical [nerve signal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_potential) that is sent to the [visual cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_cortex) in the occipital lobe. The arrangements of the eyes' optics cause light from the left [visual field](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_field) to be received by the rightmost portion of each retina, and vice versa. This arrangement ultimately means that a portion of each retina is processed by each hemisphere of the cortex, such that both the right and left visual cortex process information from both eyes. Visual signals leave the retinas through the [optic nerves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optic_nerves). Optic nerve fibres from the retinas' nasal halves [cross to the opposite sides](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optic_chiasm) joining the fibres from the temporal halves of the opposite retinas, which do not cross, forming the [optic tracts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optic_tracts). The optic tract fibres reach the brain at the [lateral geniculate nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_geniculate_nucleus), and travel through the [optic radiation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optic_radiation) to reach the visual cortex.[\[88\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011623%E2%80%93631-89)

[Hearing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hearing) and [balance](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equilibrioception) are both generated in the [inner ear](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_ear). Sound results in vibrations of the [ossicles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ossicles) which continue finally to [the hearing organ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hair_cell), and change in balance results in movement of [liquids within the inner ear](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vestibular_system). This creates a nerve signal that passes through the [vestibulocochlear nerve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vestibulocochlear_nerve). From here, it passes through to the [cochlear nuclei](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cochlear_nuclei), the [superior olivary nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superior_olivary_nucleus), the [medial geniculate nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medial_geniculate_nucleus), and finally the [auditory radiation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auditory_radiation) to the [auditory cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auditory_cortex).[\[89\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011739%E2%80%93740-90)

The sense of [smell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olfaction) is generated by [receptor cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olfactory_receptor_neuron) in the [epithelium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olfactory_epithelium) of the [olfactory mucosa](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olfactory_mucosa) in the [nasal cavity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nasal_cavity). This information passes via the [olfactory nerve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olfactory_nerve), which goes into the skull through the [cribriform plate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cribriform_plate). This nerve transmits to the neural circuitry of the [olfactory bulb](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olfactory_bulb) from where information is passed to the [olfactory cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olfactory_system).[\[90\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPocock2006138%E2%80%93139-91)[\[91\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTESquire2013525%E2%80%93526-92) [Taste](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taste) is generated from [receptors on the tongue](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taste_receptor) and passed along the [facial](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Facial_nerve) and [glossopharyngeal nerves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossopharyngeal_nerve) into the [solitary nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solitary_nucleus) in the brainstem. Some taste information is also passed from the pharynx into this area via the [vagus nerve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vagus_nerve). Information is then passed from here through the thalamus into the [gustatory cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gustatory_cortex).[\[92\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011647%E2%80%93648-93)

**Regulation**

[Autonomic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autonomic_nervous_system) functions of the brain include the regulation, or [rhythmic control](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroscience_of_rhythm) of the [heart rate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heart_rate) and [rate of breathing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Respiratory_rate), and maintaining [homeostasis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homeostasis).

[Blood pressure](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_pressure) and [heart rate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heart_rate) are influenced by the [vasomotor centre](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vasomotor_center) of the medulla, which causes arteries and veins to be somewhat constricted at rest. It does this by influencing the [sympathetic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sympathetic_nervous_system) and [parasympathetic nervous systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parasympathetic_nervous_system) via the [vagus nerve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vagus_nerve).[\[93\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011202%E2%80%93203-94) Information about blood pressure is generated by [baroreceptors](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baroreceptor) in [aortic bodies](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aortic_body) in the [aortic arch](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aortic_arch), and passed to the brain along the [afferent fibres](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_visceral_afferent_fibers) of the vagus nerve. Information about the pressure changes in the [carotid sinus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carotid_sinus) comes from [carotid bodies](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carotid_body) located near the [carotid artery](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_carotid_artery) and this is passed via a [nerve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hering%27s_nerve) joining with the [glossopharyngeal nerve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossopharyngeal_nerve). This information travels up to the [solitary nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solitary_nucleus) in the medulla. Signals from here influence the vasomotor centre to adjust vein and artery constriction accordingly.[\[94\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011205%E2%80%93208-95)

The brain controls the [rate of breathing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Respiratory_rate), mainly by [respiratory centres](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Respiratory_center) in the medulla and pons.[\[95\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011505%E2%80%93509-96) The respiratory centres control [respiration](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Respiration_\(physiology\)), by generating motor signals that are passed down the spinal cord, along the [phrenic nerve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phrenic_nerve) to the [diaphragm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thoracic_diaphragm) and other [muscles of respiration](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muscles_of_respiration). This is a [mixed nerve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal_nerve) that carries sensory information back to the centres. There are four respiratory centres, three with a more clearly defined function, and an apneustic centre with a less clear function. In the medulla a dorsal respiratory group causes the desire to [breathe in](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inhalation) and receives sensory information directly from the body. Also in the medulla, the ventral respiratory group influences [breathing out](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exhalation) during exertion. In the pons the [pneumotaxic centre](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pneumotaxic_center) influences the duration of each breath,[\[95\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011505%E2%80%93509-96) and the [apneustic centre](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apneustic_center) seems to have an influence on inhalation. The respiratory centres directly senses blood [carbon dioxide](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_dioxide) and [pH](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PH). Information about blood [oxygen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxygen), [carbon dioxide](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_dioxide) and pH levels are also sensed on the walls of arteries in the [peripheral chemoreceptors](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peripheral_chemoreceptor) of the aortic and carotid bodies. This information is passed via the vagus and glossopharyngeal nerves to the respiratory centres. High carbon dioxide, an acidic pH, or low oxygen stimulate the respiratory centres.[\[95\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011505%E2%80%93509-96) The desire to breathe in is also affected by [pulmonary stretch receptors](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulmonary_stretch_receptor) in the lungs which, when activated, prevent the lungs from overinflating by transmitting information to the respiratory centres via the vagus nerve.[\[95\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011505%E2%80%93509-96)

The [hypothalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypothalamus) in the [diencephalon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diencephalon), is involved in regulating many functions of the body. Functions include [neuroendocrine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroendocrine) regulation, regulation of the [circadian rhythm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circadian_rhythm), control of the [autonomic nervous system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autonomic_nervous_system), and the regulation of fluid, and food intake. The circadian rhythm is controlled by two main cell groups in the hypothalamus. The anterior hypothalamus includes the [suprachiasmatic nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suprachiasmatic_nucleus) and the [ventrolateral preoptic nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventrolateral_preoptic_nucleus) which through gene expression cycles, generates a roughly 24 hour [circadian clock](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circadian_clock). In the [circadian day](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circadian_clock) an [ultradian rhythm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultradian_rhythm) takes control of the sleeping pattern. [Sleep](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sleep) is an essential requirement for the body and brain and allows the closing down and resting of the body's systems. There are also findings that suggest that the daily build-up of toxins in the brain are removed during sleep.[\[96\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-sleep-97) Whilst awake the brain consumes a fifth of the body's total energy needs. [Sleep](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroscience_of_sleep) necessarily reduces this use and gives time for the restoration of energy-giving [ATP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenosine_triphosphate). The effects of [sleep deprivation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sleep_deprivation) show the absolute need for sleep.[\[97\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011723-98)

The [lateral hypothalamus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_hypothalamus) contains [orexinergic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orexin) neurons that control [appetite](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Appetite) and [arousal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arousal) through their projections to the [ascending reticular activating system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ascending_reticular_activating_system).[\[98\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Davis-99)[\[99\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTESquire2013800-100) The hypothalamus controls the [pituitary gland](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pituitary_gland) through the release of peptides such as [oxytocin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxytocin), and [vasopressin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vasopressin), as well as [dopamine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dopamine) into the [median eminence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median_eminence). Through the autonomic projections, the hypothalamus is involved in regulating functions such as blood pressure, heart rate, breathing, sweating, and other homeostatic mechanisms.[\[100\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTESquire2013803-101) The hypothalamus also plays a role in thermal regulation, and when stimulated by the immune system, is capable of generating a [fever](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fever). The hypothalamus is influenced by the kidneys: when blood pressure falls, the [renin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renin) released by the kidneys stimulates a need to drink. The hypothalamus also regulates food intake through autonomic signals, and hormone release by the digestive system.[\[101\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTESquire2013805-102)

**Language**

**![][image13]**

[Broca's area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broca%27s_area) and [Wernicke's area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wernicke%27s_area) are linked by the [arcuate fasciculus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arcuate_fasciculus).

*Main article: [Language processing in the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_processing_in_the_brain)*

*See also: [Two-streams hypothesis § Two auditory systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-streams_hypothesis#Two_auditory_systems)*

While language functions were traditionally thought to be localised to [Wernicke's area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wernicke%27s_area) and [Broca's area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broca%27s_area),[\[102\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGuyton_&_Hall2011720%E2%80%932-103) it is now mostly accepted that a wider network of [cortical](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cortex_\(anatomy\)) regions contributes to language functions.[\[103\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-104)[\[104\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-105)[\[105\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-106)

The study on how language is represented, processed, and [acquired](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_acquisition) by the brain is called [neurolinguistics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurolinguistics), which is a large multidisciplinary field drawing from [cognitive neuroscience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognitive_neuroscience), [cognitive linguistics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognitive_linguistics), and [psycholinguistics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psycholinguistics).[\[106\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-107)

**Lateralisation**

*Main article: [Lateralization of brain function](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateralization_of_brain_function)*

*Further information: [Functional specialization (brain)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_specialization_\(brain\))*

*See also: [Contralateral brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contralateral_brain)*

The cerebrum has a [contralateral organisation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contralateral_brain) with each hemisphere of the brain interacting primarily with one half of the body: the left side of the brain interacts with the right side of the body, and vice versa. This is theorized to be caused by a developmental [axial twist](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axial_Twist_theory).[\[107\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Lussanet2012-108) Motor connections from the brain to the spinal cord, and sensory connections from the spinal cord to the brain, both [cross sides](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decussation) in the brainstem. Visual input follows a more complex rule: the optic nerves from the two eyes come together at a point called the [optic chiasm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optic_chiasm), and half of the fibres from each nerve split off to join the other.[\[108\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-109) The result is that connections from the left half of the retina, in both eyes, go to the left side of the brain, whereas connections from the right half of the retina go to the right side of the brain.[\[109\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kolb_2-110) Because each half of the retina receives light coming from the opposite half of the visual field, the functional consequence is that visual input from the left side of the world goes to the right side of the brain, and vice versa.[\[110\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Berntson-111) Thus, the right side of the brain receives somatosensory input from the left side of the body, and visual input from the left side of the visual field.[\[111\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Sherwood-112)[\[112\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kalat-113)

The left and right sides of the brain appear symmetrical, but they function asymmetrically.[\[113\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Cowin-114) For example, the counterpart of the left-hemisphere motor area controlling the right hand is the right-hemisphere area controlling the left hand. There are, however, several important exceptions, involving language and spatial cognition. The left frontal lobe is dominant for language. If a key language area in the left hemisphere is damaged, it can leave the victim unable to speak or understand,[\[113\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Cowin-114) whereas equivalent damage to the right hemisphere would cause only minor impairment to language skills.

A substantial part of current understanding of the interactions between the two hemispheres has come from the study of "[split-brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Split-brain) patients"—people who underwent surgical transection of the corpus callosum in an attempt to reduce the severity of epileptic seizures.[\[114\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Myers-115) These patients do not show unusual behaviour that is immediately obvious, but in some cases can behave almost like two different people in the same body, with the right hand taking an action and then the left hand undoing it.[\[114\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Myers-115)[\[115\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kolb_3-116) These patients, when briefly shown a picture on the right side of the point of visual fixation, are able to describe it verbally, but when the picture is shown on the left, are unable to describe it, but may be able to give an indication with the left hand of the nature of the object shown.[\[115\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kolb_3-116)[\[116\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Schacter-117)

**Emotion**

*Main article: [Emotion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emotion)*

*Further information: [Affective neuroscience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affective_neuroscience)*

[Emotions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emotion) are generally defined as two-step multicomponent processes involving [elicitation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_intelligence_\(intelligence_gathering\)), followed by psychological feelings, appraisal, expression, autonomic responses, and action tendencies.[\[117\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-118) Attempts to localise basic emotions to certain brain regions have been controversial; some research found no evidence for specific locations corresponding to emotions, but instead found circuitry involved in general emotional processes. The [amygdala](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amygdala), [orbitofrontal cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orbitofrontal_cortex), mid and anterior [insular cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insular_cortex) and lateral [prefrontal cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prefrontal_cortex), appeared to be involved in generating the emotions, while weaker evidence was found for the [ventral tegmental area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventral_tegmental_area), [ventral pallidum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventral_pallidum) and [nucleus accumbens](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nucleus_accumbens) in [incentive salience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incentive_salience).[\[118\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-119) Others, however, have found evidence of activation of specific regions, such as the [basal ganglia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basal_ganglia) in happiness, the [subcallosal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corpus_callosum) [cingulate cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cingulate_cortex) in sadness, and [amygdala](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amygdala) in fear.[\[119\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-120)

**Cognition**

*Main article: [Cognition](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognition)*

*Further information: [Prefrontal cortex § Executive function](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prefrontal_cortex#Executive_function)*

The brain is responsible for [cognition](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognition),[\[120\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NHM_preface_-_Cognition-121)[\[121\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NHMH_3e_%E2%80%93_Higher_Cognitive_Function_and_Behavioral_Control-122) which functions through numerous [processes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognitive_process) and [executive functions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Executive_function).[\[121\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NHMH_3e_%E2%80%93_Higher_Cognitive_Function_and_Behavioral_Control-122)[\[122\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NHMH_3e_%E2%80%93_pathways-123)[\[123\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Executive_functions-124) Executive functions include the ability to filter information and tune out irrelevant stimuli with [attentional control](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attentional_control) and [cognitive inhibition](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognitive_inhibition), the ability to process and manipulate information held in [working memory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Working_memory), the ability to think about multiple concepts simultaneously and [switch tasks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Task_switching_\(psychology\)) with [cognitive flexibility](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognitive_flexibility), the ability to inhibit [impulses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impulse_\(psychology\)) and [prepotent responses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prepotent_response) with [inhibitory control](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inhibitory_control), and the ability to determine the relevance of information or appropriateness of an action.[\[122\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NHMH_3e_%E2%80%93_pathways-123)[\[123\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Executive_functions-124) Higher order executive functions require the simultaneous use of multiple basic executive functions, and include [planning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planning), [prospection](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prospection) and [fluid intelligence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_intelligence) (i.e., [reasoning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reasoning) and [problem solving](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem_solving)).[\[123\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Executive_functions-124)

The [prefrontal cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prefrontal_cortex) plays a significant role in mediating executive functions.[\[121\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NHMH_3e_%E2%80%93_Higher_Cognitive_Function_and_Behavioral_Control-122)[\[123\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Executive_functions-124)[\[124\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Goldstein-125) Planning involves activation of the [dorsolateral prefrontal cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorsolateral_prefrontal_cortex) (DLPFC), [anterior cingulate cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_cingulate_cortex), angular prefrontal cortex, right prefrontal cortex, and [supramarginal gyrus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supramarginal_gyrus).[\[124\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Goldstein-125) Working memory manipulation involves the DLPFC, [inferior frontal gyrus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inferior_frontal_gyrus), and areas of the [parietal cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parietal_cortex).[\[121\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NHMH_3e_%E2%80%93_Higher_Cognitive_Function_and_Behavioral_Control-122)[\[124\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Goldstein-125) [Inhibitory control](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inhibitory_control) involves multiple areas of the prefrontal cortex, as well as the [caudate nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caudate_nucleus) and [subthalamic nucleus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subthalamic_nucleus).[\[123\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Executive_functions-124)[\[124\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Goldstein-125)[\[125\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NHMH_3e_%E2%80%93_Addiction_and_ADHD-126)

**Physiology**

**Neurotransmission**

*Main article: [Neurotransmission](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotransmission)*

*Further information: [Summation (neurophysiology)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Summation_\(neurophysiology\))*

Brain activity is made possible by the interconnections of [neurons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuron) that are linked together to reach their targets.[\[126\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPocock200668-127) A neuron consists of a [cell body](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soma_\(biology\)), [axon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axon), and [dendrites](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dendrite). Dendrites are often extensive branches that receive information in the form of signals from the axon terminals of other neurons. The signals received may cause the neuron to initiate an [action potential](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_potential) (an electrochemical signal or nerve impulse) which is sent along its axon to the axon terminal, to connect with the dendrites or with the cell body of another neuron. An action potential is initiated at the [initial segment](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axon#Initial_segment) of an axon, which contains a specialised complex of proteins.[\[127\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-128) When an action potential reaches the axon terminal it triggers the release of a [neurotransmitter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotransmitter) at a [synapse](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synapse) that propagates a signal that acts on the target cell.[\[128\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPocock200670%E2%80%9374-129) These chemical neurotransmitters include [dopamine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dopamine), [serotonin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serotonin), [GABA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma-Aminobutyric_acid), [glutamate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glutamate_\(neurotransmitter\)), and [acetylcholine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acetylcholine).[\[129\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NIMH2017-130) GABA is the major inhibitory neurotransmitter in the brain, and glutamate is the major excitatory neurotransmitter.[\[130\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-131) Neurons link at synapses to form [neural pathways](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_pathway), [neural circuits](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_circuit), and large elaborate [network systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large-scale_brain_networks) such as the [salience network](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salience_network) and the [default mode network](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Default_mode_network), and the activity between them is driven by the process of [neurotransmission](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotransmission).

**Metabolism**

**![A flat oval object is surrounded by blue. The object is largely green-yellow, but contains a dark red patch at one end and a number of blue patches.][image14]**

[PET](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positron_emission_tomography) image of the human brain showing energy consumption

The brain consumes up to 20% of the energy used by the human body, more than any other organ.[\[131\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-power-sciam-132) In humans, [blood glucose](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_glucose) is the primary [source of energy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Food_energy) for most cells and is critical for normal function in a number of tissues, including the brain.[\[132\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Glucose-Glycogen_storage_review-133) The human brain consumes approximately 60% of blood glucose in fasted, sedentary individuals.[\[132\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Glucose-Glycogen_storage_review-133) Brain [metabolism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metabolism) normally relies upon blood [glucose](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glucose) as an energy source, but during times of low glucose (such as [fasting](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fasting), [endurance exercise](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endurance_exercise), or limited [carbohydrate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbohydrate) intake), the brain uses [ketone bodies](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ketone_bodies) for fuel with a smaller need for glucose. The brain can also utilize [lactate during exercise](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lactic_acid#Exercise_and_lactate).[\[133\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-134) The brain stores glucose in the form of [glycogen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glycogen), albeit in significantly smaller amounts than that found in the [liver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liver) or [skeletal muscle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skeletal_muscle).[\[134\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-135) [Long-chain fatty acids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatty_acid#Length_of_free_fatty_acid_chains) cannot cross the [blood–brain barrier](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood%E2%80%93brain_barrier), but the liver can break these down to produce ketone bodies. However, [short-chain fatty acids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short-chain_fatty_acid) (e.g., [butyric acid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butyric_acid), [propionic acid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propionic_acid), and [acetic acid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acetic_acid)) and the [medium-chain fatty acids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatty_acid#Length_of_free_fatty_acid_chains), [octanoic acid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octanoic_acid) and [heptanoic acid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heptanoic_acid), can cross the blood–brain barrier and be metabolised by [brain cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_cell).[\[135\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-136)[\[136\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-SCFA_MCT-mediated_BBB_passage_-_2005_review-137)[\[137\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-SCFA_MCT-mediated_BBB_passage_-_2014_review-138)

Although the human brain represents only 2% of the body weight, it receives 15% of the cardiac output, 20% of total body oxygen consumption, and 25% of total body [glucose](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glucose) utilization.[\[138\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-139) The brain mostly uses glucose for energy, and deprivation of glucose, as can happen in [hypoglycemia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypoglycemia), can result in loss of consciousness.[\[139\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Mrsulja-140) The energy consumption of the brain does not vary greatly over time, but active regions of the cortex consume somewhat more energy than inactive regions, which forms the basis for the [functional neuroimaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_neuroimaging) methods of [PET](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positron_emission_tomography) and [fMRI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FMRI).[\[140\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-141) These techniques provide a three-dimensional image of metabolic activity.[\[141\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Steptoe-142) A preliminary study showed that brain metabolic requirements in humans peak at about five years old.[\[142\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-143)

The function of [sleep](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sleep) is not fully understood; however, there is evidence that sleep enhances the clearance of metabolic waste products, some of which are potentially [neurotoxic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotoxic), from the brain and may also permit repair.[\[52\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Glymphatic_system_and_brain_waste_clearance_2017_review-53)[\[143\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-144)[\[144\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Sleep_%E2%80%93_clearance_of_neurotoxic_waste_products-145) Evidence suggests that the increased clearance of metabolic waste during sleep occurs via increased functioning of the [glymphatic system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glymphatic_system).[\[52\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Glymphatic_system_and_brain_waste_clearance_2017_review-53) Sleep may also have an effect on cognitive function by weakening unnecessary connections.[\[145\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-146)

**Sentience**
