The functions of the brain depend on adequate [sentience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sentience), where the ability of neurons to transmit electrochemical signals to other cells and their ability to respond appropriately to electrochemical signals received from other cells, are the proper response to specific input stimuli through the sensory system. Beginning from basic patterns of stimulus-response coordination, the human capacity to appropriately detect changes within themselves and their environments depends on the specific nervous system architecture. The balanced nervous system with required functions is a result of a significant developmental journey during gestation.[\[146\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Val_Danilov_Origin_Neurostimulation_2024-147) According to the influential view in cognitive sciences, the mother-fetus interaction enables the child's nervous system to grow with adequate biological sentience.[\[146\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Val_Danilov_Origin_Neurostimulation_2024-147) This physical interaction within the so-called mother-fetus neurocognitive model forms the specific architecture of the child's nervous system and contributes to developing adequate biological sentience and the beginning of cognition.[\[146\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Val_Danilov_Origin_Neurostimulation_2024-147) The most powerful physical forces of this interaction are the low-frequency pulsed electromagnetic field and complex acoustic wave of the mother's heart.[\[146\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Val_Danilov_Origin_Neurostimulation_2024-147)

**Research**

The brain is not fully understood, and research is ongoing.[\[147\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-HCP2009-148) [Neuroscientists](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroscientist), along with researchers from allied disciplines, study how the human brain works. The boundaries between the specialties of [neuroscience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroscience), [neurology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurology) and other disciplines such as [psychiatry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychiatry) have faded as they are all influenced by [basic research](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_research) in neuroscience.

Neuroscience research has expanded considerably. The "[Decade of the Brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decade_of_the_Brain)", an initiative of the United States Government in the 1990s, is considered to have marked much of this increase in research,[\[148\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-149) and was followed in 2013 by the [BRAIN Initiative](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BRAIN_Initiative).[\[149\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-150) The [Human Connectome Project](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_Connectome_Project) was a five-year study launched in 2009 to analyse the anatomical and functional connections of parts of the brain, and has provided much data.[\[147\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-HCP2009-148)

An emerging phase in research may be that of [simulating](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulation) brain activity.[\[150\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-151)

**Methods**

Information about the structure and function of the human brain comes from a variety of experimental methods, including animals and humans. Information about brain trauma and stroke has provided information about the function of parts of the brain and the effects of [brain damage](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_damage). [Neuroimaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroimaging) is used to visualise the brain and record brain activity. [Electrophysiology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrophysiology) is used to measure, record and monitor the electrical activity of the cortex. Measurements may be of [local field potentials](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_field_potential) of cortical areas, or of the activity of a single neuron. An [electroencephalogram](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electroencephalography) can record the electrical activity of the cortex using [electrodes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrode) placed non-invasively on the [scalp](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalp).[\[151\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-152)[\[152\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPurves2012632%E2%80%93633-153)

Invasive measures include [electrocorticography](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrocorticography), which uses electrodes placed directly on the exposed surface of the brain. This method is used in [cortical stimulation mapping](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cortical_stimulation_mapping), used in the study of the relationship between cortical areas and their systemic function.[\[153\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-154) By using much smaller [microelectrodes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microelectrode), [single-unit recordings](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single-unit_recording) can be made from a single neuron that give a high [spatial resolution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_resolution) and high [temporal resolution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporal_resolution). This has enabled the linking of brain activity to behaviour, and the creation of neuronal maps.[\[154\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-155)

The development of [cerebral organoids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_organoid) has opened ways for studying the growth of the brain, and of the cortex, and for understanding disease development, offering further implications for therapeutic applications.[\[155\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Lancaster-156)[\[156\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Lee-157)

**Imaging**

*Further information: [Magnetic resonance imaging of the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_resonance_imaging_of_the_brain)*

*![][image15]*

FMRI of healthy human brain

[Functional neuroimaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_neuroimaging) techniques show changes in brain activity that relate to the function of specific brain areas. One technique is [functional magnetic resonance imaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_magnetic_resonance_imaging) (fMRI) which has the advantages over earlier methods of [SPECT](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SPECT) and [PET](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positron_emission_tomography) of not needing the use of [radioactive materials](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_medicine) and of offering a higher resolution.[\[157\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-158) Another technique is [functional near-infrared spectroscopy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_near-infrared_spectroscopy). These methods rely on the [haemodynamic response](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haemodynamic_response) that shows changes in brain activity in relation to changes in [blood flow](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_circulation), useful in [mapping functions to brain areas](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_mapping).[\[158\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-159) [Resting state fMRI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resting_state_fMRI) looks at the interaction of brain regions whilst the brain is not performing a specific task.[\[159\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-160) This is also used to show the [default mode network](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Default_mode_network).

Any electrical current generates a magnetic field; [neural oscillations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_oscillation) induce weak magnetic fields, and in functional [magnetoencephalography](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetoencephalography) the current produced can show localised brain function in high resolution.[\[160\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPurves201220-161) [Tractography](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tractography) uses [MRI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MRI) and [image analysis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_analysis) to create [3D images](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/3D_modeling) of the [nerve tracts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nerve_tract) of the brain. [Connectograms](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connectogram) give a graphical representation of the [neural connections](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connectome) of the brain.[\[161\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kane-162)

Differences in [brain structure can be measured](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_morphometry) in some disorders, notably [schizophrenia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schizophrenia) and [dementia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dementia). Different biological approaches using imaging have given more insight for example into the disorders of [depression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology_of_depression) and [obsessive-compulsive disorder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology_of_obsessive-compulsive_disorder). A key source of information about the function of brain regions is the effects of damage to them.[\[162\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-163)

Advances in [neuroimaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroimaging) have enabled objective insights into mental disorders, leading to faster diagnosis, more accurate prognosis, and better monitoring.[\[163\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-164)

**Gene and protein expression**

*Main article: [Bioinformatics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bioinformatics)*

*See also: [List of neuroscience databases](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_neuroscience_databases)*

[Bioinformatics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bioinformatics) is a field of study that includes the creation and advancement of databases, and computational and statistical techniques, that can be used in studies of the human brain, particularly in the areas of [gene and protein expression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bioinformatics#Gene_and_protein_expression). Bioinformatics and studies in [genomics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genomics), and [functional genomics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_genomics), generated the need for [DNA annotation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA_annotation), a [transcriptome technology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcriptomics_technologies), identifying [genes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene), their locations and functions.[\[164\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Steward-165)[\[165\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-166)[\[166\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Gibson_and_Muse-167) [GeneCards](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GeneCards) is a major database.

As of 2017, just under 20,000 [protein-coding genes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_genome#Coding_sequences_\(protein-coding_genes\)) are seen to be expressed in the human,[\[164\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Steward-165) and some 400 of these genes are brain-specific.[\[167\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-168)[\[168\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-169) The data that has been provided on [gene expression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene_expression) in the brain has fuelled further research into a number of disorders. The long term use of alcohol for example, has shown altered gene expression in the brain, and cell-type specific changes that may relate to [alcohol use disorder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcoholism).[\[169\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-170) These changes have been noted in the [synaptic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synapse) [transcriptome](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcriptome) in the prefrontal cortex, and are seen as a factor causing the drive to alcohol dependence, and also to other [substance abuses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Substance_abuse).[\[170\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-171)

Other related studies have also shown evidence of synaptic alterations and their loss, in the [ageing brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ageing_brain). Changes in gene expression alter the levels of proteins in various neural pathways and this has been shown to be evident in synaptic contact dysfunction or loss. This dysfunction has been seen to affect many structures of the brain and has a marked effect on inhibitory neurons resulting in a decreased level of neurotransmission, and subsequent cognitive decline and disease.[\[171\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Rozycka-172)[\[172\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-173)

**Clinical significance**

**Injury**

[Injury to the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_damage) can manifest in many ways. [Traumatic brain injury](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traumatic_brain_injury), for example received in [contact sport](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contact_sport), after a [fall](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falling_\(accident\)), or a [traffic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traffic_collision) or [work accident](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Work_accident), can be associated with both immediate and longer-term problems. Immediate problems may include [bleeding within the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intracerebral_haemorrhage), this may compress the brain tissue or damage its blood supply. [Bruising](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_contusion) to the brain may occur. Bruising may cause widespread damage to the nerve tracts that can lead to a condition of [diffuse axonal injury](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffuse_axonal_injury).[\[173\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-GE_Health-174) A [fractured skull](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skull_fracture), injury to a particular area, [deafness](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deafness), and [concussion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concussion) are also possible immediate developments. In addition to the site of injury, the opposite side of the brain may be affected, termed a [contrecoup injury](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coup_contrecoup_injury). Longer-term issues that may develop include [posttraumatic stress disorder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posttraumatic_stress_disorder), and [hydrocephalus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrocephalus). [Chronic traumatic encephalopathy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chronic_traumatic_encephalopathy) can develop following multiple [head injuries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Head_injury).[\[174\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-175)

**Disease**

[Neurodegenerative diseases](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurodegenerative_disease) result in progressive damage to, or loss of neurons affecting different functions of the brain, that [worsen with age](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aging_brain). Common types are [dementias](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dementia) including [Alzheimer's disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alzheimer%27s_disease), [alcoholic dementia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcoholic_dementia), [vascular dementia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vascular_dementia), and [Parkinson's disease dementia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parkinson%27s_disease_dementia). Other rarer infectious, genetic, or metabolic types include [Huntington's disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huntington%27s_disease), [motor neuron diseases](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_neuron_disease), [HIV dementia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HIV_dementia), [syphilis-related dementia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurosyphilis) and [Wilson's disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilson%27s_disease). Neurodegenerative diseases can affect different parts of the brain, and can affect movement, [memory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memory), and cognition.[\[175\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101196%E2%80%937-176) Rare [prion diseases](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prion_disease) including [Creutzfeldt–Jakob disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creutzfeldt%E2%80%93Jakob_disease) and its [variant](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variant_Creutzfeldt%E2%80%93Jakob_disease), and [kuru](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kuru_\(disease\)) are fatal neurodegenerative diseases.[\[176\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101205%E2%80%9315-177)

[Cerebral atherosclerosis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_atherosclerosis) is [atherosclerosis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atherosclerosis) that affects the brain. It results from the build-up of [plaques](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atheroma) formed of [cholesterol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cholesterol), in the large arteries of the brain, and can be mild to significant. When significant, arteries can become narrowed enough to reduce blood flow. It contributes to the development of dementia, and has protein similarities to those found in Alzheimer's disease.[\[177\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NN2020-178)

The brain, although protected by the blood–brain barrier, can be affected by infections including [viruses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virus), [bacteria](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacteria) and [fungi](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fungi). Infection may be of the [meninges](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meninges) ([meningitis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meningitis)), the brain matter ([encephalitis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encephalitis)), or within the brain matter (such as a [cerebral abscess](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_abscess)).[\[176\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101205%E2%80%9315-177)

**Tumours**

[Brain tumours](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_tumor) can be either [benign](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benign) or [cancerous](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malignant). Most malignant tumours [arise from another part of the body](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metastasis), most commonly from the [lung](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lung_cancer), [breast](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breast_cancer) and [skin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanoma).[\[178\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101216%E2%80%937-179) Cancers of brain tissue can also occur, and originate from any tissue in and around the brain. [Meningioma](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meningioma), cancer of the meninges around the brain, is more common than cancers of brain tissue.[\[178\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101216%E2%80%937-179) Cancers within the brain may cause symptoms related to their size or position, with symptoms including headache and nausea, or the gradual development of focal symptoms such as gradual difficulty seeing, swallowing, talking, or as a change of mood.[\[178\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101216%E2%80%937-179) Cancers are in general investigated through the use of CT scans and MRI scans. A variety of other tests including blood tests and lumbar puncture may be used to investigate for the cause of the cancer and evaluate the type and [stage](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cancer_staging) of the cancer.[\[178\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101216%E2%80%937-179) The [corticosteroid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corticosteroid) [dexamethasone](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dexamethasone) is often given to decrease the [swelling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oedema) of brain tissue around a tumour. Surgery may be considered, however given the complex nature of many tumours or based on tumour stage or type, [radiotherapy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiotherapy) or [chemotherapy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemotherapy) may be considered more suitable.[\[178\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101216%E2%80%937-179)

**Mental disorders**

[Mental disorders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mental_disorder), such as [depression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_depressive_disorder), [schizophrenia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schizophrenia), [bipolar disorder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bipolar_disorder), [posttraumatic stress disorder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posttraumatic_stress_disorder), [attention deficit hyperactivity disorder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attention_deficit_hyperactivity_disorder), [obsessive-compulsive disorder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obsessive-compulsive_disorder), [Tourette syndrome](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tourette_syndrome), and [addiction](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addiction), are known to relate to the functioning of the brain.[\[125\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NHMH_3e_%E2%80%93_Addiction_and_ADHD-126)[\[129\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NIMH2017-130)[\[179\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Addiction_-_brain_disease_review-180) Treatment for mental disorders may include [psychotherapy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychotherapy), [psychiatry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychiatry), [social intervention](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_interventionism) and personal [recovery](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recovery_model) work or [cognitive behavioural therapy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognitive_behavioural_therapy); the underlying issues and associated prognoses vary significantly between individuals.[\[180\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Simpson-181)

**Epilepsy**

[Epileptic seizures](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epileptic_seizure) are thought to relate to abnormal electrical activity.[\[181\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101172%E2%80%939-182) Seizure activity can manifest as [absence of consciousness](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absence_seizure), [focal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focal_seizure) effects such as limb movement or impediments of speech, or be [generalized](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalised_seizure) in nature.[\[181\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101172%E2%80%939-182) [Status epilepticus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Status_epilepticus) refers to a seizure or series of seizures that have not terminated within five minutes.[\[182\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-foundation-183) Seizures have a large number of causes, however many seizures occur without a definitive cause being found. In a person with [epilepsy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epilepsy), risk factors for further seizures may include sleeplessness, drug and alcohol intake, and stress. Seizures may be assessed using [blood tests](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_test), [EEG](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EEG) and various [medical imaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_imaging) techniques based on the [medical history](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_history) and [medical examination](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_examination) findings.[\[181\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101172%E2%80%939-182) In addition to treating an underlying cause and reducing exposure to risk factors, [anticonvulsant](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anticonvulsant) medications can play a role in preventing further seizures.[\[181\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101172%E2%80%939-182)

**Congenital**

Some brain disorders, such as [Tay–Sachs disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tay%E2%80%93Sachs_disease),[\[183\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Moore-184) are [congenital](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congenital_disorder) and linked to [genetic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutation) and [chromosomal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromosome_abnormality) mutations.[\[184\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Pennington-185) A rare group of congenital [cephalic disorders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cephalic_disorder) known as [lissencephaly](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lissencephaly) is characterised by the lack of, or inadequacy of, cortical folding.[\[185\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Govaert-186) Normal [development](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prenatal_development) of the brain can be affected during [pregnancy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pregnancy) by [nutritional deficiencies](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nutritional_deficiencies),[\[186\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Perese-187) [teratogens](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teratology),[\[187\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kearney-188) [infectious diseases](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infectious_diseases),[\[188\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Stevenson-189) and by the use of [recreational drugs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recreational_drug_use), including alcohol (which may result in [fetal alcohol spectrum disorders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fetal_alcohol_spectrum_disorders)).[\[186\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Perese-187)[\[189\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Dewhurst-190) Most [cerebral arteriovenous malformations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_arteriovenous_malformation) are congenital, these tangled networks of blood vessels may remain without symptoms but at their worst may rupture and cause [intracranial hemorrhaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intracranial_hemorrhage).[\[190\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-NINDS-191)

**Stroke**

*Main article: [Stroke](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroke)*

*![][image16]*

[CT scan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CT_scan) of a [cerebral hemorrhage](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebral_hemorrhage), showing an [intraparenchymal bleed](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intraparenchymal_bleed) (bottom arrow) with surrounding [edema](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edema) (top arrow)

A [stroke](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroke) is a [decrease in blood supply](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ischemia) to an area of the brain causing [cell death](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_death) and [brain injury](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_damage#Causes). This can lead to a wide range of [symptoms](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroke#Signs_and_symptoms), including the "[FAST](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FAST_\(stroke\))" symptoms of facial droop, arm weakness, and speech difficulties (including [with speaking](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysarthria) and [finding words or forming sentences](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysphasia)).[\[191\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-192) Symptoms relate to the function of the affected area of the brain and can point to the likely site and cause of the stroke. Difficulties with movement, speech, or sight usually relate to the cerebrum, whereas [imbalance](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ataxia), [double vision](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diplopia), [vertigo](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertigo) and symptoms affecting more than one side of the body usually relate to the brainstem or cerebellum.[\[192\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101183-193)

Most strokes result from loss of blood supply, typically because of an [embolus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embolus), rupture of a [fatty plaque](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atheroma) causing [thrombus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thrombus), or [narrowing of small arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arteriosclerotic). Strokes can also result from [bleeding within the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroke#Hemorrhagic).[\[193\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101180%E2%80%931-194) [Transient ischaemic attacks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transient_ischemic_attack) (TIAs) are strokes in which symptoms resolve within 24 hours.[\[193\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101180%E2%80%931-194) Investigation into the stroke will involve a [medical examination](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_examination) (including a [neurological examination](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurological_examination)) and the taking of a [medical history](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_history), focusing on the duration of the symptoms and risk factors (including [high blood pressure](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypertension), [atrial fibrillation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atrial_fibrillation), and [smoking](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tobacco_smoking)).[\[194\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101181,_1183%E2%80%931185-195) Further investigation is needed in younger patients.[\[195\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101183%E2%80%931185-196) An [ECG](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ECG) and [biotelemetry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biotelemetry) may be conducted to identify [atrial fibrillation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atrial_fibrillation); an [ultrasound](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultrasound) can investigate [narrowing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carotid_stenosis) of the [carotid arteries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_carotid_artery); an [echocardiogram](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Echocardiogram) can be used to look for clots within the heart, [diseases of the heart valves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valvular_heart_disease) or the presence of a [patent foramen ovale](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patent_foramen_ovale).[\[195\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101183%E2%80%931185-196) [Blood tests](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_test) are routinely done as part of the [workup](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_diagnosis#Other_diagnostic_procedure_methods) including [diabetes tests](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diabetes_mellitus#Diagnosis) and a [lipid profile](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lipid_profile).[\[195\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101183%E2%80%931185-196)

Some treatments for stroke are time-critical. These include [clot dissolution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thrombolysis) or [surgical removal of a clot](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embolectomy) for [ischaemic strokes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_ischemia), and [decompression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decompression_\(surgery\)) for [haemorrhagic strokes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intracranial_hemorrhage).[\[196\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101185%E2%80%931189-197)[\[197\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-198) As stroke is time critical,[\[198\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-199) hospitals and even pre-hospital care of stroke involves expedited investigations – usually a [CT scan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CT_scan) to investigate for a haemorrhagic stroke and a [CT](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CT_angiogram) or [MR angiogram](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MR_angiogram) to evaluate arteries that supply the brain.[\[195\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101183%E2%80%931185-196) [MRI scans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MRI_scan), not as widely available, may be able to demonstrate the affected area of the brain more accurately, particularly with ischaemic stroke.[\[195\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101183%E2%80%931185-196)

Having experienced a stroke, a person may be admitted to a [stroke unit](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroke_unit), and treatments may be directed as [preventing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secondary_prevention) future strokes, including ongoing [anticoagulation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anticoagulation) (such as [aspirin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aspirin) or [clopidogrel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clopidogrel)), [antihypertensives](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antihypertensive_drug), and [lipid-lowering drugs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lipid-lowering_agent).[\[196\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101185%E2%80%931189-197) A [multidisciplinary team](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academic_discipline#Multidisciplinary) including [speech pathologists](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speech_pathologist), [physiotherapists](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physiotherapists), [occupational therapists](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occupational_therapist), and [psychologists](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychologist) plays a large role in supporting a person affected by a stroke and their [rehabilitation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_medicine_and_rehabilitation).[\[199\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-200)[\[195\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101183%E2%80%931185-196) A history of stroke increases the risk of developing dementia by around 70%, and recent stroke increases the risk by around 120%.[\[200\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-201)

**Brain death**

*Main article: [Brain death](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_death)*

Brain death refers to an irreversible total loss of brain function.[\[201\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-GOILA2009-202)[\[202\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-:0-203) This is characterised by [coma](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coma), loss of [reflexes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflex), and [apnoea](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apnoea),[\[201\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-GOILA2009-202) however, the declaration of brain death varies geographically and is not always accepted.[\[202\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-:0-203) In some countries there is also a defined syndrome of [brainstem death](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brainstem_death).[\[203\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-204) Declaration of brain death can have profound implications as the declaration, under the principle of [medical futility](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Futile_medical_care), will be associated with the withdrawal of life support,[\[204\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101158-205) and as those with brain death often have organs suitable for [organ donation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organ_donation).[\[202\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-:0-203)[\[205\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's2010200-206) The process is often made more difficult by poor communication with patients' families.[\[206\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Urden-207)

When brain death is suspected, reversible [differential diagnoses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_diagnosis) such as, electrolyte, neurological and drug-related cognitive suppression need to be excluded.[\[201\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-GOILA2009-202)[\[204\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101158-205) Testing for reflexes[\[b\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-208) can be of help in the decision, as can the absence of response and breathing.[\[204\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavidson's20101158-205) Clinical observations, including a total lack of responsiveness, a known diagnosis, and [neural imaging](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_imaging) evidence, may all play a role in the decision to pronounce brain death.[\[201\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-GOILA2009-202)

**Society and culture**

[Neuroanthropology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroanthropology) is the study of the relationship between culture and the brain. It explores how the brain gives rise to culture, and how culture influences brain development.[\[207\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-209) Cultural differences and their relation to brain development and structure are researched in different fields.[\[208\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Cultural-210)

**The mind**

*Main articles: [Cognition](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognition) and [Mind](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mind)*

*![][image17]*

The skull of [Phineas Gage](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phineas_Gage), with the path of the iron rod that passed through it without killing him, but altering his cognition. The case helped to convince people that mental functions were localised in the brain.[\[209\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Macmillan-211)

The [philosophy of the mind](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy_of_mind) studies such issues as the problem of understanding [consciousness](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consciousness) and the [mind–body problem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mind%E2%80%93body_problem). The relationship between the brain and the [mind](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mind) is a significant challenge both philosophically and scientifically. This is because of the difficulty in explaining how mental activities, such as thoughts and emotions, can be implemented by physical structures such as neurons and [synapses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synapse), or by any other type of physical mechanism. This difficulty was expressed by [Gottfried Leibniz](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Leibniz) in the analogy known as *Leibniz's Mill*:

One is obliged to admit that perception and what depends upon it is inexplicable on mechanical principles, that is, by figures and motions. In imagining that there is a machine whose construction would enable it to think, to sense, and to have perception, one could conceive it enlarged while retaining the same proportions, so that one could enter into it, just like into a windmill. Supposing this, one should, when visiting within it, find only parts pushing one another, and never anything by which to explain a perception.

— Leibniz, [Monadology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monadology)[\[210\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-212)

Doubt about the possibility of a mechanistic explanation of thought drove [René Descartes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes), and most other philosophers along with him, to [dualism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dualism_\(philosophy_of_mind\)): the belief that the mind is to some degree independent of the brain.[\[211\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-213) There has always, however, been a strong argument in the opposite direction. There is clear empirical evidence that physical manipulations of, or injuries to, the brain (for example by drugs or by lesions, respectively) can affect the mind in potent and intimate ways.[\[212\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Churchland-214)[\[213\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-215) In the 19th century, the case of [Phineas Gage](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phineas_Gage), a railway worker who was injured by a stout iron rod passing through his brain, convinced both researchers and the public that cognitive functions were localised in the brain.[\[209\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Macmillan-211) Following this line of thinking, a large body of empirical evidence for a close relationship between brain activity and mental activity has led most neuroscientists and contemporary philosophers to be [materialists](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Materialism), believing that mental phenomena are ultimately the result of, or reducible to, physical phenomena.[\[214\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-216)

**Brain size**

*Main article: [Brain size](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_size)*

The size of the brain and a person's [intelligence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intelligence) are not strongly related.[\[215\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-217) Studies tend to indicate small to moderate [correlations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation) (averaging around 0.3 to 0.4) between brain volume and [IQ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intelligence_quotient).[\[216\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-218) The most consistent associations are observed within the frontal, temporal, and parietal lobes, the hippocampi, and the cerebellum, but these only account for a relatively small amount of variance in IQ, which itself has only a partial relationship to general intelligence and real-world performance.[\[217\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-219)[\[218\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-220)

Other animals, including whales and elephants, have larger brains than humans. However, when the [brain-to-body mass ratio](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain-to-body_mass_ratio) is taken into account, the human brain is almost twice as large as that of a [bottlenose dolphin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bottlenose_dolphin), and three times as large as that of a [chimpanzee](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_chimpanzee). However, a high ratio does not of itself demonstrate intelligence: very small animals have high ratios and the [treeshrew](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treeshrew) has the largest quotient of any mammal.[\[219\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-221)

**In popular culture**

[Phrenology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phrenology) summarised in an 1883 chart

Earlier ideas about the relative importance of the different [organs of the human body](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_location_of_the_soul) sometimes emphasised the heart.[\[220\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-222) Modern Western popular conceptions, in contrast, have placed increasing focus on the [brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mind-brain_dichotomy).[\[221\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-223)

Research has disproved some common [misconceptions about the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_common_misconceptions#Brain). These include both ancient and modern myths. It is not true (for example) that neurons are not replaced after the age of two; nor that normal humans use only [ten per cent of the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ten_percent_of_the_brain_myth).[\[222\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-224) Popular culture has also oversimplified the [lateralisation of the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateralization_of_brain_function) by suggesting that functions are completely specific to one side of the brain or the other. [Akio Mori](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akio_Mori) coined the term "[game brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_brain)" for the unreliably supported theory that spending long periods playing [video games](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game) harmed the brain's pre-frontal region, and impaired the expression of emotion and creativity.[\[223\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-225)

Historically, particularly in the early-19th century, the brain featured in popular culture through [phrenology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phrenology), a [pseudoscience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudoscience) that assigned personality attributes to different regions of the cortex. The cortex remains important in popular culture as covered in books and satire.[\[224\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-226)[\[225\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-227)

The human brain can feature in [science fiction](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_in_science_fiction), with themes such as [brain transplants](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain_transplant) and [cyborgs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyborgs_in_fiction) (beings with features like partly [artificial brains](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_brain)).[\[226\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-228) The 1942 science-fiction book (adapted three times for the cinema) [*Donovan's Brain*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donovan%27s_Brain) tells the tale of an [isolated brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isolated_brain) kept alive *in vitro*, gradually taking over the personality of the book's protagonist.[\[227\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-229)

**History**

*Main article: [History of neuroscience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_neuroscience)*

**Early history**

[Hieroglyph](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hieroglyph) for the word "brain" (c. 1700 BC)

The [Edwin Smith Papyrus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edwin_Smith_Papyrus), an [ancient Egyptian](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Egypt) [medical treatise](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_literature) written in the 17th century BC, contains the earliest recorded reference to the brain. The [hieroglyph](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hieroglyph) for brain, occurring eight times in this papyrus, describes the symptoms, diagnosis, and prognosis of two traumatic injuries to the head. The papyrus mentions the external surface of the brain, the effects of injury (including seizures and [aphasia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aphasia)), the meninges, and cerebrospinal fluid.[\[228\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kandel-230)[\[229\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Adelman-231)

In the fifth century BC, [Alcmaeon of Croton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcmaeon_of_Croton) in [Magna Grecia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magna_Grecia), first considered the brain to be the [seat of the mind](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensorium).[\[229\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Adelman-231) Also in the [fifth century BC in Athens](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fifth-century_Athens), the unknown author of [*On the Sacred Disease*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_the_Sacred_Disease), a medical treatise which is part of the [Hippocratic Corpus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippocratic_Corpus) and traditionally attributed to [Hippocrates](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippocrates), believed the brain to be the seat of intelligence. [Aristotle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle), in his [biology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle%27s_biology) initially believed the heart to be the seat of [intelligence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intelligence), and saw the brain as a cooling mechanism for the blood. He reasoned that humans are more rational than the beasts because, among other reasons, they have a larger brain to cool their hot-bloodedness.[\[230\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Bear-232) Aristotle did describe the meninges and distinguished between the cerebrum and cerebellum.[\[231\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-233)

[Herophilus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herophilus) of [Chalcedon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chalcedon) in the fourth and third centuries BC distinguished the cerebrum and the cerebellum, and provided the first clear description of the [ventricles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventricular_system); and with [Erasistratus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erasistratus) of [Ceos](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kea_\(island\)) experimented on living brains. Their works are now mostly lost, and we know about their achievements due mostly to secondary sources. Some of their discoveries had to be re-discovered a millennium after their deaths.[\[229\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Adelman-231) Anatomist physician [Galen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galen) in the second century AD, during the time of the [Roman Empire](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Empire), dissected the brains of sheep, monkeys, dogs, and pigs. He concluded that, as the cerebellum was denser than the brain, it must control the [muscles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muscle), while as the cerebrum was soft, it must be where the senses were processed. Galen further theorised that the brain functioned by movement of animal spirits through the ventricles.[\[229\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Adelman-231)[\[230\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Bear-232)

In 2025, scientists reported the discovery of a preserved human brain from the [eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 79 AD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eruption_of_Mount_Vesuvius_in_79_AD). A man in [Herculaneum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herculaneum) was caught in a [pyroclastic flow](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyroclastic_flow), and the extremely high temperature caused the [vitrification](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vitrification) of his brain, turning it into [glass](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glass) and resulting in "a perfect state of preservation of the brain and its microstructures."[\[232\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Giordano-234) It appears to have been the only known case of a vitrified human brain.[\[232\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Giordano-234)[\[233\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-235)

**Renaissance**

Drawing of the base of the brain, from [Andreas Vesalius](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andreas_Vesalius)'s 1543 work [*De humani corporis fabrica*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_humani_corporis_fabrica)

One of [Leonardo da Vinci](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonardo_da_Vinci)'s sketches of the human skull

In 1316, [Mondino de Luzzi](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mondino_de_Luzzi)'s *Anathomia* began the modern study of brain anatomy.[\[234\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-236) [Niccolò Massa](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niccol%C3%B2_Massa) discovered in 1536 that the ventricles were filled with fluid.[\[235\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-LOKHORST2016-237) [Archangelo Piccolomini](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archangelo_Piccolomini) of [Rome](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rome) was the first to distinguish between the cerebrum and cerebral cortex.[\[236\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Gross1999-238) In 1543 [Andreas Vesalius](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andreas_Vesalius) published his seven-volume [*De humani corporis fabrica*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_humani_corporis_fabrica).[\[236\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Gross1999-238)[\[237\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-MARSHALL-239)[\[238\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-240) The seventh book covered the brain and eye, with detailed images of the ventricles, cranial nerves, [pituitary gland](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pituitary_gland), meninges, structures of the [eye](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_eye), the vascular supply to the brain and spinal cord, and an image of the peripheral nerves.[\[239\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-tessman-241) Vesalius rejected the common belief that the ventricles were responsible for brain function, arguing that many animals have a similar ventricular system to humans, but no true intelligence.[\[236\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Gross1999-238)

[René Descartes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes) proposed the theory of [dualism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mind-body_dualism) to tackle the issue of the brain's relation to the mind. He suggested that the [pineal gland](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pineal_gland) was where the mind interacted with the body, serving as the seat of the soul and as the connection through which [animal spirits](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animism) passed from the blood into the brain.[\[235\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-LOKHORST2016-237) This dualism likely provided impetus for later anatomists to further explore the relationship between the anatomical and functional aspects of brain anatomy.[\[240\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-OCONNOR2003-242)

[Thomas Willis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Willis) is considered a second pioneer in the study of neurology and brain science. He wrote *Cerebri Anatome* ([Latin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_language): *Anatomy of the brain*)[\[c\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-243) in 1664, followed by *Cerebral Pathology* in 1667\. In these he described the structure of the cerebellum, the ventricles, the cerebral hemispheres, the brainstem, and the cranial nerves, studied its blood supply; and proposed functions associated with different areas of the brain.[\[236\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Gross1999-238) The circle of Willis was named after his investigations into the blood supply of the brain, and he was the first to use the word "neurology".[\[241\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Emery2000-244) Willis removed the brain from the body when examining it, and rejected the commonly held view that the cortex only consisted of blood vessels, and the view of the last two millennia that the cortex was only incidentally important.[\[236\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Gross1999-238)

In the middle of 19th century [Emil du Bois-Reymond](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emil_du_Bois-Reymond) and [Hermann von Helmholtz](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_von_Helmholtz) were able to use a [galvanometer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galvanometer) to show that electrical impulses passed at measurable speeds along nerves, refuting the view of their teacher [Johannes Peter Müller](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Peter_M%C3%BCller) that the nerve impulse was a vital function that could not be measured.[\[242\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-245)[\[243\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-246)[\[244\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-247) [Richard Caton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Caton) in 1875 demonstrated electrical impulses in the cerebral hemispheres of rabbits and monkeys.[\[245\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-248) In the 1820s, [Jean Pierre Flourens](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Pierre_Flourens) pioneered the experimental method of damaging specific parts of animal brains describing the effects on movement and behavior.[\[246\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-249)

**Modern period**

*Further information: [Neuropsychiatry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuropsychiatry)*

Drawing by [Camillo Golgi](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camillo_Golgi) of vertical section of rabbit [hippocampus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippocampus), from his "Sulla fina anatomia degli organi centrali del sistema nervoso", 1885

Drawing of cells in chick [cerebellum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellum) by [Santiago Ramón y Cajal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santiago_Ram%C3%B3n_y_Cajal), from "Estructura de los centros nerviosos de las aves", Madrid, 1905

Studies of the brain became more sophisticated with the use of the [microscope](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microscope) and the development of a [silver staining](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silver_stain) [method](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golgi_method) by [Camillo Golgi](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camillo_Golgi) during the 1880s. This was able to show the intricate structures of single neurons.[\[247\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-DECARLOS2007-250) This was used by [Santiago Ramón y Cajal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santiago_Ram%C3%B3n_y_Cajal) and led to the formation of the [neuron doctrine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuron_doctrine), the then revolutionary hypothesis that the neuron is the functional unit of the brain. He used microscopy to uncover many cell types, and proposed functions for the cells he saw.[\[247\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-DECARLOS2007-250) For this, Golgi and Cajal are considered the founders of [twentieth century neuroscience](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_neuroscience), both sharing the [Nobel prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_prize) in 1906 for their studies and discoveries in this field.[\[247\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-DECARLOS2007-250)

[Charles Sherrington](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Scott_Sherrington) published his influential 1906 work *The Integrative Action of the Nervous System* examining the function of reflexes, evolutionary development of the nervous system, functional specialisation of the brain, and layout and cellular function of the central nervous system.[\[248\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-251) In 1942 he coined the term [*enchanted loom*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enchanted_loom) as a metaphor for the brain. [John Farquhar Fulton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Farquhar_Fulton), founded the *Journal of Neurophysiology* and published the first comprehensive textbook on the physiology of the nervous system during 1938\.[\[249\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-SQUIRE1996-252) [Neuroscience during the twentieth century](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_neuroscience#Twentieth_century) began to be recognised as a distinct unified academic discipline, with [David Rioch](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Rioch), [Francis O. Schmitt](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_O._Schmitt), and [Stephen Kuffler](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Kuffler) playing critical roles in establishing the field.[\[250\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-COWAN2000-253) Rioch originated the integration of basic anatomical and physiological research with clinical psychiatry at the [Walter Reed Army Institute of Research](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Reed_Army_Institute_of_Research), starting in the 1950s.[\[251\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-254) During the same period, Schmitt established the [Neuroscience Research Program](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroscience_Research_Program), an inter-university and international organisation, bringing together biology, medicine, psychological and behavioural sciences. The word neuroscience itself arises from this program.[\[252\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-255)

[Paul Broca](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Broca) associated regions of the brain with specific functions, in particular language in [Broca's area](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broca%27s_area), following work on brain-damaged patients.[\[253\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Neural_Science_2000-256) [John Hughlings Jackson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Hughlings_Jackson) described the function of the [motor cortex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_cortex) by watching the progression of [epileptic seizures](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epileptic_seizure) through the body. [Carl Wernicke](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Wernicke) described [a region](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wernicke%27s_area) associated with language comprehension and production. [Korbinian Brodmann](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korbinian_Brodmann) divided regions of the brain based on the appearance of cells.[\[253\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Neural_Science_2000-256) By 1950, Sherrington, [Papez](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Papez), and [MacLean](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_D._MacLean) had identified many of the brainstem and limbic system functions.[\[254\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Papez-257)[\[255\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-258) The capacity of the brain to re-organise and change with age, and a recognised critical development period, were attributed to [neuroplasticity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroplasticity), pioneered by [Margaret Kennard](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Kennard), who experimented on monkeys during the 1930-40s.[\[256\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-259)

[Harvey Cushing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvey_Cushing) (1869–1939) is recognised as the first proficient [brain surgeon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurosurgery) in the world.[\[257\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-M.Bliss-260) In 1937, [Walter Dandy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Dandy) began the practice of vascular [neurosurgery](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurosurgery) by performing the first surgical clipping of an [intracranial aneurysm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intracranial_aneurysm).[\[258\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-261)

**Comparative anatomy**

*See also: [Evolution of the brain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_of_the_brain)*

The human brain has many properties that are common to all [vertebrate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertebrate) brains.[\[259\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-262) Many of its features are common to all [mammalian](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mammal) brains,[\[260\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Simpkins-263) most notably a six-layered cerebral cortex and a set of associated structures,[\[261\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Bornstein-264) including the hippocampus and [amygdala](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amygdala).[\[262\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Bernstein-265) The cortex is proportionally larger in humans than in many other mammals.[\[263\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-HOFMAN2014-266) Humans have more association cortex, sensory and motor parts than smaller mammals such as the rat and the cat.[\[264\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-267)

As a [primate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primate) brain, the human brain has a much larger cerebral cortex, in proportion to body size, than most mammals,[\[262\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Bernstein-265) and a highly developed visual system.[\[265\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Lu-268)[\[266\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Sharwood_Smith-269)

As a [hominid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hominidae) brain, the human brain is substantially enlarged even in comparison to the brain of a typical ape. The sequence of [human evolution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_evolution) from [*Australopithecus*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australopithecus) (four million years ago) to [*Homo sapiens*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human) (modern humans) was marked by a steady increase in brain size.[\[267\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Kolb_and_Whishaw-270)[\[268\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Nieuwenhuys-271) As brain size increased, this altered the size and shape of the skull,[\[269\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-Lee_Lerner-272) from about 600 [cm3](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_centimetre) in [*Homo habilis*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homo_habilis) to an average of about 1520 cm3 in [*Homo neanderthalensis*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homo_neanderthalensis).[\[270\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-273) Differences in [DNA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA), [gene expression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene_expression), and [gene–environment interactions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene%E2%80%93environment_interaction) help explain the differences between the function of the human brain and other primates.[\[271\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_brain#cite_note-274)
